This thread is dedicated to all animals of the reptilia and amphibia classes. Topics include, but are not limited to: geckos, snakes of all kinds, frogs, salamanders, newts, turtles, tortoises, and much more. Before asking a question, do a search on the internet to see if it has been answered
Classifieds for finding breeders and products:
>morphmarket.com
>kingsnake.com
>faunaclassifieds.com
>reptilescanada.com (Canadian breeders)
>caudata.org
Most forums will have a "for sale" section on them, so look for that, especially if you have a specific herp you want. Craigslist can also be a good source for cheap aquariums, and make sure to check for any reptile expos that occur in your area.

When asking a question, make sure to include these details:
>Type and size of animal
>Enclosure dimensions
>Humidity and temperature
>Type of substrate
>The decor you use
>How often you feed
>The type of food you use
>If your animal is wild caught or captive bred
>How often you handle
>Who you bought the animal from

http://www.hylid.clara.co.uk/caer.htm

http://blogs.thatpetplace.com/thatreptileblog/

com:
Dearest botanists & herbalists of /an/,

Hypothetically speaking, if I were on an expedition to colonize the Late Cretaceous (so 65 million years ago'ish) what kind of flora would me and my team be able to forage for? Lets just assume for the sake of the argument that we 100% know the Dinosaurs, Fish, and other fauna are all perfectly edible (as is their giant flintstones-tier eggs), but what we need to know is plants. Has fruit been invented yet? What do we have for nuts, edible grasses, etc? Does grass exist yet, or if it does is it simply too primitive and obscure?

Or would it just be better for us to bring some seeds back with us?

Because fairly certain if anybody *is* going to get killed by a Dinosaur it's probably going to be getting ambushed in the dense brush. In 2010, 19-year-old Sam, an avid rugby player, was drinking with Jimmy Galvin and several more of his Australian “mates” when a slug began crawling across Galvin’s concrete patio at his home in Sydney.

“We were sitting over here, having a bit of red wine appreciation night, trying to act as grown-ups. And then the conversation came up, ‘Should I eat it?’ ” recalled Galvin. “And then off Sam went and bang, that’s how it happened.”

After downing the slug, Sam became weak and complained of severe pain in his legs, according to “The Sunday Project.” Sam’s mother, Katie Ballard, told the news show that at first they worried he might have multiple sclerosis, which had afflicted her husband. But doctors said no, that wasn’t the cause.

Then Sam turned to his mother and told her he had eaten a slug, “And I went, ‘No, no one gets sick from that,’ ” Katie Ballard said. CNN has also reached out to Ballard.

Soon, however, doctors told them otherwise. Sam had developed rat lungworm disease from the infected slug.

Soon after the diagnosis, Sam fell into a coma, where he remained for 420 days, Ballard said in the Australian news report. He woke up paralyzed, unable to eat without a tube or move without intense effort. He required 24-hour care, seven days a week.

But the disease didn’t affect his mental faculties, his family and friends said.

“He’s in there, 100%,” Galvin told “The Sunday Project.” “I apologized to Sam about everything that happened that night in the backyard. And he just started bawling his eyes out. I know he’s there.”

“Sam passed away on Friday morning at Hornsby Hospital, not far from where he grew up, surrounded by 20 of those he most loved in the world,” she wrote.

Like the other guys were saying the easiest and most fool proof way is to just leave the old enclosure open in the new, but if the sizes don't permit or she won't move after a while you can just get a decent sized stick and coax her onto it then put that into the new enclosure. Just make sure you do the transfer inside some kind of plastic tub in case she falls or drops down to play dead, they can't climb plastic well if at all so that should keep her contained. Brain weight is a rough metric at best

What matters the most is the number of, the type of, and the organization of neurons. For example humans have high numbers of well organized spindle cells that create purposeful and efficient connections between distant layers of the brain. Dolphins have fewer and less organized spindle cells. This strongly implies an inferior form of consciousness, so despite their massive brain it's mostly just an information processor optimized for sonar with less information integration and they are about as aware of their own machinations as a chimp with a much smaller (slightly denser and more organized) brain.

Sometimes it evens out with different skills being selected for. Pig brains have a lot of fat and a little extra white matter, dog brains have more neuron density and gray matter. Pigs do not need to be taught to solve problems, but their social skills are severely lacking. Dogs need to be taught to solve problems and can do dumb shit like not even really try to solve a problem until encouraged to. What good is passing the mirror test if you sit there thinking "what if i shouldn't pass the mirror test" until someone eggs you on? However, their social skills are excellent.', 'time': 1670608205, 'resto': 4375855}]

However, this kitten is stressing me out majorly. He’s a kitten so of course he’s crazy jumping everywhere and I can’t even eat because he takes my food from me (kek). He tears my curtains, climbs my counters and runs laps around the place. I can’t rest and destress from the move because the cat needs constant attention. On top of that I have horrible anxiety and I’m constantly worried something will happen to him. I can’t go for a walk because he gets stressed if I leave the room. I also read that he’s the most playful breed, which I stupidly didn’t research beforehand as I just wanted a calm cat to keep me company (my family cat is a total low effort lazy boy).

He’s a sweetie and lies in my lap as I work, and loves me even after knowing me for such a short time. I do have thoughts of giving him back because I’m so damn stressed on the verge of a mental breakdown, and I didn’t really think before getting this cat. I feel really bad because he’s not a bad cat, im just an anxious bitch that made an impulsive choice.

What can I do to help us both ease into living together? How do I calm down? I feel like I have the animal version of post partum depression.

>The idea that pitbulls are nanny dogs originates from a 1971 New York Times article with the headline "A Breed That Came Up the Hard Way". A spokesman for a Staffordshire Bull Terrier club was talking about that breed, and she claimed they're known as "nursemaid dogs".

Yeah, and it's very interesting the pit breeders started pushing this notion around the same time when dog fighting was slowly becoming illegal. Most states had banned it in the 1960s and by 1976 it was illegal across the USA - so the breed, known for being the best dog fighting breed, needed and image revamp, and so they invented the "nanny dog" myth and started aggressively pushing it, in order to make pits and staffies etc seem palatable as a household pet, to keep up demand', 'time': 1670530744, 'resto': 4367611}, {'no': 4375186, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)15:21:48', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4367613

last_replies:
[{'no': 4374821, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)03:00:41', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'she killed hundreds...', 'time': 1670486441, 'resto': 4374802}, {'no': 4374879, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)04:17:19', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'hey i wanna know too, would love to pet the moomoos', 'time': 1670491039, 'resto': 4374802}, {'no': 4374889, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)04:47:15', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'saw a kid get his knee cap kicked out of alignment in agriculture class year 9', 'time': 1670492835, 'resto': 4374802}, {'no': 4374912, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)05:42:58', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'Being around cows is usually safe if you're not an idiot and many cows love to be pet, but you shouldn't just go up to strange cows and try to get close to them. Most cattle breeds are pretty timid and can be easily spooked by unfamiliar things, and the last thing you want is for a thousand+ pound wall of muscle to run over you in a panic. Mother cows with calves and bulls are especially dangerous. But if you establish trust and show the cattle that you're not a threat, they can be very friendly and affectionate.
That said. if you want to pet a cow, you're probably best off going to a petting zoo or a farm that offers tours. This thread is dedicated to all animals of the reptilia and amphibia classes. Topics include, but are not limited to: geckos, snakes of all kinds, frogs, salamanders, newts, turtles, tortoises, and much more. Before asking a question, do a search on the internet to see if it has been answered
Classifieds for finding breeders and products:
>morphmarket.com
>kingsnake.com
>faunaclassifieds.com
>reptilescanada.com (Canadian breeders)

Most forums will have a "for sale" section on them, so look for that, especially if you have a specific herp you want. Craigslist can also be a good source for cheap aquariums, and make sure to check for any reptile expos that occur in your area.

When asking a question, make sure to include these details:
>Type and size of animal
>Enclosure dimensions
>Humidity and temperature
>Type of substrate
>The decor you use
>How often you feed
>The type of food you use
>If your animal is wild caught or captive bred
>How often you handle
>Who you bought the animal from
